# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1920-chicago-white-sox-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 season was the seventh season overall for the Chicago White Sox, and their sixth season in the major leagues.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won their second American League pennant and their first World Series championship.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won 93 games in the regular season–– a plateau they would not reach again until the 1915 season–– to claim the pennant, propelled by a historic 19-game winning streak in August.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] They won the league pennant largely on the strength of their pitching staff, as their team batting average of .230 was the worst in the AL.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 White Sox team became known as the *Hitless Wonders*, having won the American League pennant despite posting the lowest team batting average (.230) in the league.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team had been in fourth place by the end of July, 7½ games behind the defending champion Philadelphia Athletics, when they went on a 19-game winning streak that drove them into first place.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] No American League team would beat the 19-game winning streak for almost 100 years.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team made up for their lack of hitting prowess by leading the league in walks, hit batsmen and sacrifice hits.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox pitching staff had a league-leading 32 shutouts and the second lowest earned run average in the league.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox then defeated their cross-town rivals, the heavily favored Chicago Cubs in the 1906 World Series.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1920 Chicago White Sox season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The team was in contention to defend their American League pennant going into the final week of the season.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] However, for all intents and purposes, the season ended on September 26, when news of the Black Sox Scandal became public.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The team finished with a record of 96-58, which was not only the best record during Comiskey's ownership (and the best finish of the Gleason era), but would remain a franchise record for the next 44 years until 1964 when the Sox won 98 games.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] Owner Charles Comiskey suspended the five players who were still active (the sixth, ringleader Chick Gandil, opted to retire after the 1919 season).
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] At that time, the White Sox were only a half-game behind the Cleveland Indians, but went 2–2 over their last four games to finish two games out.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] They would not finish in the first division again until 1936.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1920 White Sox are one of only two teams in baseball history (The other being the 1971 Baltimore Orioles) to have four 20-game winners: Red Faber, Lefty Williams, Eddie Cicotte, and Dickie Kerr.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] Shoeless Joe Jackson finished third in AL batting average, and Eddie Collins was fifth.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] Louis Browns, the team was the first in major league history to have three players with at least 200 hits each: Jackson, Collins, and Buck Weaver.
[src:1920-chicago-white-sox-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox became the first team to have four 20-game winners in the same pitching rotation.
